The subjunctive, in its simplest and apparently most primitive use, seen in Homer (284), expresses futurity, like the future indicative, and has οὐ for its negative. E.g.,
*ou) ga/r pw toi/ous i)/don a)ne/ras ou)de\ i)/dwmai, for never did I see such men nor shall I ever see them, Il. i. 262 ;
kai/ pote/ tis ei)/ph|sin, and some one will some time say, Il. vi. 459.

div2.p:
Here again we see what the change is, for we represent it by
                            our change from is to was, have to had, shall and
                                will to should and would, etc.; as λέγει ὅτι ἀληθές ἐστιν,
                                he says that it is true;
                            ἔλεξεν ὅτι ἀληθὲς
                            εἴη (or ἐστίν),
                                he said that it was true;
                            λέγει ὅτι γράψει, he says that he will write;
                            ἔλεξεν ὅτι γράψοι (or
                                γράψει), he said that he would write. So οὐκ οἶδα τί εἴπω, I know not what I shall say;
                            οὐκ ᾔδειν τί εἴποιμι
                            (or εἴπω), I knew not what I should say.

The present indicative represents an action as going on at the time of speaking or writing;
                            as γράφω, I write, or I am
                                writing.

(a) The perfect of many verbs has the signification of a
                            present, which may usually be explained by the peculiar meaning of the
                            verbs. Thus θνῄσκειν,
                                to die, τεθνηκέναι, to be
                                dead;
                            καλεῖν, to call, κεκλῆσθαι, to be called or
                                named;
                            γίγνεσθαι, to become, γεγονέναι, to be;
                            μιμνῄσκειν, to remind, μεμνῆσθαι, to
                                remember;
                            εἰδέναι, to know;
                            ἱστάναι, to place, ἑστάναι, to
                            stand. So βεβηκέναι, to stand;
                            ἐγνωκέναι, to know;
                            ἠμφιέσθαι, to wear;
                            κεκτῆσθαι, to possess;
                            πεποιθέναι, to trust;
                            πεφυκέναι, to be (by nature); etc.

The present and aorist here differ only in this, that the present expresses an action in its duration, that is, as going on or repeated, while the aorist expresses simply its occurrence, the time of both tenses being otherwise precisely the same. E.g.
Ἐὰν ποιῇ τοῦτο, if he shall be doing this, or if he shall do this (habitually);
ἐὰν ποιήσῃ τοῦτο, (simply) if he shall do this;
εἰ ποιοίη τοῦτο, if he should be doing this, or if he should do this (habitually);
εἰ ποιήσειε τοῦτο, if he should do this;
ποίει τοῦτο, do this (habitually);
ποίησον τοῦτο, do this.
Οὕτω νικήσαιμί τ’ ἐγὼ καὶ νομιζοίμην σοφός, on this condition may I gain the victory (aorist) and be considered (present) wise.
AR. Nub. 520. *bou/letai tou=to poiei=n , he wishes to do this (habitually);
βούλεται τοῦτο ποιῆσαι, (simply) he wishes to do this. For other examples see below.

(As Present.) The present infinitive in indirect discourse generally represents a present indicative of the direct form. E.g.
Φησὶ γράφειν, he says that he is writing;
ἔφη γράφειν, he said that he was writing;
φήσει γράφειν, he will say that he is (then) writing. (In all three cases he says γράφω.)
Ἀρρωστεῖν προφασίζεται, he pretends that he is sick;
e)cw/mosen a)rrwstei=n toutoni/, he took his oath that this man was sick. DEM. xix. 124.
*ou)k e)/fh au)to\s a)ll' e)kei=non strathgei=n he said that not he himself, but Nicias, was general; i.e. he said οὐκ ἐγὼ αὐτὸς ἀλλ’ ἐκεῖνος στρατηγεῖ. THUC. iv. 28.
See other examples under 683.

The first person of the subjunctive is used in questions of appeal, where the speaker asks
                            himself or another what he is to do. The
                            negative is μή. In Attic
                            Greek this subjunctive is often introduced by βούλει or βούλεσθε, sometimes in poetry by θέλεις or θέλετε. E.g. Εἴπω τοῦτο;
                             shall I say this? or βούλει εἴπω τοῦτο;
                             do you wish that I should say this?
                            Μὴ τοῦτο ποιῶμεν (or
                                ποιήσωμεν); shall we not do this?
                            Τί εἴπω; or τί βούλεσθε εἴπω;
                             what shall I say? or what do you want me to say?

So with κελεύετε: Ἀλλὰ πῶς;
                                εἴπω κελεύετε καὶ οὐκ ὀργιεῖσθε;
                             do you command me to speak, and will you not be angry?
                            DEM. ix. 46.

Εἴ τις κλέπτοι,
                                ἐκολάζετο, if (ever) any one stole, he
                                was (in all such cases) punished;
                            εἴ τις πράσσοι (or πράξειε) τοιοῦτόν τι, ἐχαλεπαίνομεν αὐτῷ,
                                if (ever)
                                any one did such a thing, we were (always) angry with him;
                            εἴ τις τούτου πίοι,
                                ἀπέθνῃσκεν, if any one
                                (ever) drank of
                                this, he died. (See 462.)

In the lyric and elegiac poets, as in Homer, the form with ἄν or κέ was in good use in these sentences. See
PIND. Py. i. 100 o(\s a)\n e)gku/rsh| ,
v. 65 oi(=s a)\n e)qe/lh| ;
MIMN. ii. 9,
MIMN. iii. 1 e)ph\n paramei/yetai ;
SOL. xiii. 75;
THEOGN. 405,
SOL. 406 a(\ me\n h)=| kaka\, . . . a(\ d' a)\n h)=| xrh/sima . (For ordinary protasis see 469 and 470.) In the dramatists the relative with ἄν is completely established with the subjunctive as the regular form (like ἐάν, etc.) in both general and particular conditions. (See 471.)

(a) after primary tenses, each
                            verb retains both the mood and the tense of the direct discourse, no
                            change being made except (when necessary) in the person of the verb;

1. After primary tenses the verb
                            stands in the indicative, in the tense of the direct discourse. E.g.
                                Λέγει ὅτι γράφει,
                                he says that he is writing;
                            λέγει ὅτι ἔγραφεν,
                                he says that he was writing;
                            λέγει ὅτι γέγραφεν,
                                he says that he has written;
                            λέγει ὅτι ἐγεγράφει,
                                he says that he had written;
                            λέγει ὅτι ἔγραψεν,
                                he says that he wrote;
                            λέγει ὅτι γράψει, he says that he shall write.

Φησὶ (φήσει) γράψειν, he
                            says (or will say) that he will write;
                            ἔφη γράψειν, he said that he would write. (He says γράψω.)

Ἐμοὶ δοκεῖν
                            or (less frequently) ὡς ἐμοὶ
                                δοκεῖν means in my opinion, it seems
                                to me. Other similar expressions are (ὡς) εἰκάσαι, to make a guess;
                                (ὡς) συμβάλλειν, to compare, if we may
                                compare; (ὡς)
                                ἀκοῦσαι, to the ear;
                            ὡς ἰδεῖν or ὅσον ἰδεῖν, to the eye, in
                                appearance;
                            ὅσον ἐμὲ εἰδέναι,
                                so far as my knowledge goes;
                            ὡς τεκμήρασθαι, so far as one can judge. E.g.

Certain temporal participles, agreeing with the subject of a
                            sentence, have almost the force of adverbs. Such are ἀρχόμενος, at
                                first;
                            τελευτῶν, at last, finally;
                            διαλιπὼν (or ἐπισχὼν) χρόνον, after a
                                while, or διαλείπων
                                χρόνον, at intervals;
                            χρονίζων, for a long time. E.g.

1. Οὐκ ἔχω, οὐκ ἔστι with the dative, and similar expressions, in the sense of ἀπορῶ, may be followed by a deliberative subjunctive in an indirect question; as οὐκ ἔχω ὅ τι εἴπω or οὐκ ἔχω τί φῶ, I know not what to say, non habeo quod (or quid) dicam, ὅ τι here being purely interrogative like τί. This subjunctive can become an optative after a past tense or another optative; as ou)k ei)/xomen o(/tou e)pilaboi/meqa, DEM. XXXV. 25. Besides the examples in 677 we have the following.
Οὐκ ἔχοιμεν ἂν ὅποι σωθῶμεν and ou)x e(/cousin o(/poi fu/gwsin, XEN. An. ii. 4, 19 (involving ποῖ σωθῶμεν; and ποῖ φύγωμεν;).
